# The Paycheck Protection Program: An Examination of SBA Released Data in Python

## The Context:

In the aftermath of COVID, businesses in need of help applied for SBA
backed loans under the Paycheck Protection Program (PPP).[^1] The loans
were intended to be forgiven if the business met specific criteria.[^2] The
program was extended, in the form of a second round-- abbreviated as PPS
where business could apply for *more* support.

[^1]: Paycheck Protection Program Overview:

    <https://home.treasury.gov/system/files/136/PPP%20--%20Overview.pdf>

[^2]: Business Loan Program Temporary Changes; Paycheck Protection
    Program-Requirements-Loan Forgiveness:\
    <https://www.federalregister.gov/documents/2020/06/01/2020-11536/business-loan-program-temporary-changes-paycheck-protection-program-requirements-loan-forgiveness>

As the PPP program launched, the internet boomed with rumors of businesses
applying for loans (knowing they'd be forgiven) and creating job posts
(with ridiculous requirements) in order to meet one of the forgiveness
criteria.

The Small Business Administration, with assistance of The Office of
Inspector General, released a report in 2023 informing the public, the SBA
had disbursed a total of \$200 billion to fraudulent claims. While the
report was exclusively about blatant falsification of details (false EIN,
false addresses, etc). The SBA released a public list of all companies that
applied and received PPP loan funds in 2020. Updated regularly– with its
last update being on October 24th 2024.

While the dataset is quite large, it could prove impossible to truly say
whether there is more fraud than the report outlined– even if the whispers
of the internet could be true. Yet, in the spirit of examining the
businesses that submitted claims, and with an abundance of options I'll
focus on examining the Rural/Urban Indicator and whether or not there is a
significant difference in loan forgiveness amount depending on
classification.

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

::: {.callout-important appearance="simple" icon="false"}
Two separate analyses were performed using R and the results were as
follows.

1\) There **was a significant difference** in PPP loan forgiveness
contingent on the proportion of missing values within the application.
Answering all the questions in the PPP Loan Forgiveness application seemed
to significantly impact the proportion of forgiveness of the loan.

![](images/clipboard-60343285.png)

*(p-value at approximately 0, and a 95% confidence interval
ranging from 7380.743 to 8022.796) We **reject the null hypothesis**)*

2\) There was **not a significant difference** in PPP loan forgiveness
between claims from businesses classified as being in a HubZone (at
economic disadvantage) vs businessess that were not in a HubZone.

![](images/clipboard-713779731.png){width="513"}

*"With a P value at 0.16 at the alpha level of 0.05– I am 95% confident
that the businesses who are part of a HubZone have an average difference
in the proportion forgiven of their PPP Loan between -0.0044 and
0.000731. The interval includes zero, suggesting there is not a
significant difference in proportion of loan forgiven. We fail to reject
the null hypothesis."*
:::

### Changing the Data Types

`ProcessingMethod`, `LMIIndicator`, `RuralUrbanIndicator`, `LoanStatus`,
and `ProcessingMethod` are categorical. `BorrowerState` and `BorrowerName`
will be string values, and `ForgivenessAmount` will remain as float.

```{python}
category_columns = ['ProcessingMethod','LMIIndicator', 'RuralUrbanIndicator', 'LoanStatus'] 

dataP1[category_columns] = dataP1[category_columns].astype('category')

print(dataP1.info())

analysis= pd.DataFrame(dataP1, columns= ['RuralUrbanIndicator', 'CurrentApprovalAmount','ForgivenessAmount'])
analysis.head()
```

We should narrow down the columns that will be relevant for this analysis.
To find a significant difference in PPP loan forgiveness amount proportion,
between businesses classified as Rural and those classified as Urban, we'll
need `RuralUrbanIndicator` column. Our examination will include the first
ans second round of the PPP but we'll need `Processing Method` to groupby
and we'll ofcourse need `ForgivenessAmount`column.

# Hypothesis Testing

### Preparing for Hypothesis Test

```{python}
''' Calculating the Proportion of Forgiveness because Rural ocunt and Urban counts are not the same. This way the proportions are normalized. ''' 
#Proportion 
analysis.loc[:,'ProportionForgiven'] = analysis['ForgivenessAmount'] / analysis['CurrentApprovalAmount']

#Taking a Look again
analysis.head()

#Finding Mean proportions for each group 
analysis[['RuralUrbanIndicator', 'ProportionForgiven']].groupby('RuralUrbanIndicator').mean()
```

There is a difference, businesses classified as Rural have an average loan
forgiveness proportion of 1.004602 and Urban classified businesses have
1.002102. Lets see if its a significant difference.

### Hypothesis Statement

-   *Null Hypothesis:*

    There is no significant difference in the average loan forgiveness
    proportion between businesses categorized as 'Urban' and businesses
    categorized as 'Rural'.

-   *Alt Hypothesis:*

    There is a significant difference in the average loan forgiveness
    proportion between businesses categorized as 'Urban' and businesses
    categorized as 'Rural'.

### Observation Differences

# Calculate observed difference

```{python}
mean_R = analysis.loc[analysis['RuralUrbanIndicator'] == 'R', 'ProportionForgiven'].mean() 
mean_U = analysis.loc[analysis['RuralUrbanIndicator'] == 'U', 'ProportionForgiven'].mean() 
obs_diff = mean_R - mean_U 
print(f"Observed Difference in Means: {obs_diff}")
```

### NULL Distribution

The Null distribution below is and attempt to replicate the infer package
in R (treat its results lightly). The distribution is to have 1000
permutations so its been added as the range and stored in perm_diffs. as
the code loops it adds the result of the mean(with no replacements, to the
list finds the differnces in the next group.

```{python}
print(analysis.isna().sum())

analysis.dropna(inplace=True)

from sklearn.utils import shuffle
```

# Convert to NumPy arrays[^3]

[^3]: Computer couldn't handle the permutations done with slicing, did it
    with np arrays instead
    <https://stackoverflow.com/questions/21567842/is-there-a-performance-difference-between-numpy-and-pandas>

```{python}
proportion_forgiven = np.array(analysis['ProportionForgiven']) 
rural_urban_indicator = np.array(analysis['RuralUrbanIndicator'])
```

# Observed difference in means

```{python}
group_R = proportion_forgiven[rural_urban_indicator == 'R'] 
group_U = proportion_forgiven[rural_urban_indicator == 'U'] 
observed_diff = np.mean(group_R) - np.mean(group_U)

```

# Permutation test

```{python}
n_permutations = 10000 
perm_diffs = []

for _ in range(n_permutations):
  shuffled_labels = shuffle(rural_urban_indicator)
  perm_group_R = proportion_forgiven[shuffled_labels == 'R']
  perm_group_U = proportion_forgiven[shuffled_labels == 'U']
  perm_diff = np.mean(perm_group_R) - np.mean(perm_group_U)
  perm_diffs.append(perm_diff)
```

# Compute p-value

```{python}

perm_diffs = np.array(perm_diffs)
rounded_perm_diffs= np.round(perm_diffs, decimals= 4)
p_value = np.mean(np.abs(perm_diffs) >= np.abs(observed_diff))


print(f"Observed Difference: {observed_diff}")
print(f"P-Value: {p_value}")
```

We've got a p value of 0 and an observed difference of 0.0032. So far we're
rejecting the null hypothesis that there is no significant difference in
PPP loan forgiveness amount between businesses classified as Urban and
bisunesses classified as Rural. There seems to be a significant difference
but lets compute the confidence interval.[^4]

[^4]: Confidence interval after permutation:

    <https://medium.com/>@whystudying/resampling-with-python-permutation-test-19421dc38dac

Because we did permutation, our confidence interval will be alot easier to
do because we will use percentiles.

```{python}

lower = np.percentile(rounded_perm_diffs, 2.5)
upper = np.percentile(rounded_perm_diffs, 97.5)


print(f"95% Confidence Interval: [{lower}, {upper}]")
```

My initial calculations returned a p-value of 0 and a confidence interval
that included zero, as you can see below:

![](Screen Shot 2024-12-16 at 9.51.18 PM.png){width="400"}\
![](Screen Shot 2024-12-16 at 9.50.59 PM.png){width="407"}

The P value of approximately zero which indicated something was not right.
I felt we might be better served by increasing the permutations for the
sake of accuracy. I increased my permutations from 1000 to 10,000. When I
recomputed the values, I again saw the same.

```{python}

#null
plt.hist(perm_diffs, bins=100, color='lightseagreen', alpha=0.7, label='Null Distribution')

#obs
plt.axvline(observed_diff, color='darkblue', linestyle='solid', linewidth=2, label=f"Observed Diff: {observed_diff:.6f}")

#ci
plt.axvline(lower, color='darkcyan', linestyle='dotted', linewidth=1, label="95% CI Lower")
plt.axvline(upper, color='darkcyan', linestyle='dotted', linewidth=1, label="95% CI Upper")

plt.title("Null Distribution")
plt.xlabel("Difference in Means")
plt.ylabel("Frequency")
plt.legend()
plt.show()

```

The plot shows that the distribution is visibly narroe, close to normal I
believe, as it seems bell shaped. However, everything is so close together
the observed difference which is also close to zero seems incredibly far
away. Notice the scale on the x axis is incredibly tiny. I'm not sure what
can be concluded with this data. At the very least we can say there is a
significant observed difference!
